DeepFake: An Introduction¶

DeepFakes refer to synthetic media where an individual's likeness is replaced with someone else's using artificial intelligence and deep learning techniques, particularly Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs). This technology can create highly realistic but fake images, audio, and videos, posing both innovative opportunities and significant ethical challenges.

Key Applications and Concerns:

  • Applications: Entertainment (special effects), education, satire, and art.
  • Concerns: Misinformation, privacy violations, political manipulation, cyberbullying, and harassment.
  • In this notebook, we will explore how to detect and analyze DeepFakes using machine learning techniques.

Setting Up the Environment First, let's set up the necessary libraries and configurations:

Setup for Image Classification Pipeline with TensorFlow and Keras¶

  1. Importing Libraries: You've imported several essential libraries for deep learning, image processing, and model evaluation.

  2. Loading and Preprocessing Data: We need to load and preprocess the image data for training, validation, and testing. This involves using ImageDataGenerator for data augmentation and rescaling.

  3. Model Building: We will build a convolutional neural network (CNN) using Sequential and layers from Keras. Additionally, we can use a pre-trained model like ResNet50 for transfer learning.

  4. Training the Model: The model will be trained using an optimizer (e.g., Adam) and callbacks such as ModelCheckpoint and ReduceLROnPlateau.

  5. Evaluation and Metrics: After training, we evaluate the model's performance using accuracy, Cohen's kappa score, and other relevant metrics.

# Importing necessary libraries for image handling and plotting
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
import random
import os

# Function to view a random image from a specified directory
def view_random_image(target_dir, target_class):
    # Construct the path to the target class folder
    target_folder = target_dir + "/" + target_class
    print(f"Target folder: {target_folder}")  # Print the path for debugging
    
    # Select one random image from the target folder
    random_image = random.sample(os.listdir(target_folder), 1)
    
    # Read the selected image
    img = mpimg.imread(target_folder + "/" + random_image[0])
    
    # Display the image using matplotlib
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.title(target_class)  # Set the title of the plot to the class name
    plt.axis("off")  # Turn off axis ticks and labels
    
    # Print the shape of the image (dimensions and channels) for debugging
    print(f"Image shape: {img.shape}")
    
    # Return the image array
    return img

# Example usage of the function (currently commented out)

Setting Up Image Data Generators for Augmentation and Preprocessing in TensorFlow¶

In [4]:
# Importing the ImageDataGenerator class for image data preprocessing and augmentation
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Setting a random seed for reproducibility
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# Configuring the data augmentation for training images
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255,          # Normalize pixel values to [0, 1]
    rotation_range=20,                                       # Randomly rotate images by up to 20 degrees
    width_shift_range=0.2,                                  # Randomly shift images horizontally by 20% of the width
    height_shift_range=0.2,                                 # Randomly shift images vertically by 20% of the height
    shear_range=0.2,                                        # Randomly apply shear transformations
    zoom_range=0.2,                                         # Randomly zoom in on images by 20%
    horizontal_flip=True)                                   # Randomly flip images horizontally

# Configuring the validation data generator (no augmentation, only normalization)
valid_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)          # Normalize pixel values to [0, 1]

# Configuring the test data generator (no augmentation, only normalization)
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)           # Normalize pixel values to [0, 1]

# Loading training data from the specified directory
train_data = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(train_dir,   # Directory containing training images
                                               batch_size=32,  # Number of images to yield per batch
                                               target_size=(224, 224),  # Resize images to 224x224 pixels
                                               class_mode="binary",  # Binary classification (two classes)
                                               seed=42)  # Ensure reproducibility

# Loading validation data from the specified directory
valid_data = valid_datagen.flow_from_directory(valid_dir,   # Directory containing validation images
                                               batch_size=32,  # Number of images to yield per batch
                                               target_size=(224, 224),  # Resize images to 224x224 pixels
                                               class_mode="binary",  # Binary classification (two classes)
                                               seed=42)  # Ensure reproducibility

# Loading test data from the specified directory
test_data = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(test_dir,      # Directory containing test images
                                               batch_size=1,   # Number of images to yield per batch (1 for test)
                                               target_size=(224, 224),  # Resize images to 224x224 pixels
                                               class_mode="binary",  # Binary classification (two classes)
                                               shuffle=False,  # Do not shuffle test data
                                               seed=42)  # Ensure reproducibility

CNN model (model_1)¶

using TensorFlow/Keras with a Tiny VGG-like architecture. It's configured for binary classification and uses image data generators (train_data and valid_data) for training and validation.

In [5]:
# Import TensorFlow and set a random seed for reproducibility
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# Create a CNN model (similar to Tiny VGG architecture)
model_1 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
  # First convolutional layer: 20 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=20, 
                         kernel_size=3, # Kernel size can be (3, 3)
                         activation="relu", 
                         input_shape=(224, 224, 3)), # Input shape specifies height, width, and color channels
                         
  # Second convolutional layer: 20 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(20, 3, activation="relu"),
  
  # Max pooling layer: downsample with a pool size of 2
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=2, # Pool size can be (2, 2)
                             padding="valid"), # No padding; 'same' would pad to keep size
  
  # Third convolutional layer: 20 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(20, 3, activation="relu"),
  
  # Fourth convolutional layer: 20 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(20, 3, activation="relu"), # ReLU activation applied
                              
  # Second max pooling layer: downsample with a pool size of 4
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(4),
  
  # Flatten layer: converts the 3D output to a 1D array
  tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
  
  # Dense layer: 1 output unit with sigmoid activation for binary classification
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid") # Sigmoid output for binary classification
])

# Compile the model with binary crossentropy loss and Adam optimizer
model_1.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", # Loss function for binary classification
                optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(), # Optimizer
                metrics=["accuracy"]) # Metric to evaluate during training

# Fit the model on the training data
history_1 = model_1.fit(train_data,
                        epochs=5, # Number of epochs for training
                        steps_per_epoch=128, # Number of batches per epoch
                        validation_data=valid_data, # Validation data for evaluating the model
                        validation_steps=128) # Number of validation batches per epoch

# Function to load and preprocess an image
def load_and_prep_image(filename, img_shape=224):
  # Print the filename for debugging
  print(filename)
  
  # Read the image file
  img = tf.io.read_file(filename)

  # Decode the image into a tensor with 3 color channels
  img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3)
  
  # Resize the image to the specified shape (default 224x224)
  img = tf.image.resize(img, size=[img_shape, img_shape])
  
  # Normalize pixel values to the range [0, 1]
  img = img / 255.0
  
  return img  # Return the preprocessed image

Evaluating Model Performance: Confusion Matrix and Metrics Calculation¶

The code defines a function, gen_test_data, which evaluates the performance of a trained model on test data by generating predictions and various metrics. Key steps include:

  1. Predictions: The model predicts outcomes on the test dataset.
  2. Confusion Matrix: It computes and displays a confusion matrix to visualize prediction results.
  3. ROC AUC and Precision Scores: It calculates and prints the ROC AUC score and average precision score to assess classification performance.
  4. Classification Report: It provides a detailed classification report, including precision, recall, and F1-score.
  5. Model Evaluation: Finally, it evaluates the model's accuracy on the test data and prints the result.

The function is then called to execute these evaluations for the trained model.

In [7]:
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Function to generate various performance metrics and a confusion matrix from model predictions
def gen_test_data(model):
    # Generate predictions from the model on the test data
    y_pred = model.predict(test_data)
    
    # Get the true labels from the test data
    y_test = test_data.classes
    
    # Convert predicted probabilities to binary labels (1 if probability > 0.5, else 0)
    y_pred_labels = (y_pred > 0.5).astype(np.float32)

    # Calculate the confusion matrix based on true and predicted labels
    confusion_mat = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_labels)
    
    # Print the confusion matrix
    print(confusion_mat)
    
    # Display the confusion matrix visually
    cm_display = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=confusion_mat, display_labels=[False, True])
    cm_display.plot()  # Plot the confusion matrix
    plt.show()  # Show the plot
    
    # Calculate and print the ROC AUC score
    print("ROC AUC Score:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred))
    
    # Calculate and print the Average Precision score
    print("AP Score:", metrics.average_precision_score(y_test, y_pred))
    
    # Print a detailed classification report including precision, recall, and F1-score
    print()
    print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_pred_labels))
    
    # Evaluate the model on the test data and print the final accuracy
    _, accu = model.evaluate(test_data)
    print('Final Test Accuracy = {:.3f}'.format(accu * 100))  # Format and print accuracy

# Call the function to generate test data metrics for the trained model
gen_test_data(model_1)

import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np
from tensorflow import keras

# Save the trained model in Keras format to the specified path
model_1.save("/kaggle/working/VGG_01_FINAL.keras")

# Function to load and preprocess an image
def load_and_prep_image(filename, img_shape=224):
    # Print the filename being loaded for debugging purposes
    print(f"Loading image: {filename}")
    # Read the image file
    img = tf.io.read_file(filename)
    # Decode the image into a tensor with 3 channels (RGB)
    img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3)
    # Resize the image to the target shape
    img = tf.image.resize(img, size=[img_shape, img_shape])
    # Normalize pixel values to be in the range [0, 1]
    img = img / 255.0
    return img

# Load and preprocess a specific test image from the directory
test_img = load_and_prep_image(f"{test_dir}/Real/real_4.jpg")
# Add a batch dimension to the image tensor for model input
test_img = tf.expand_dims(test_img, axis=0)

# Load the saved model from the specified path
reconstructed_model = keras.models.load_model("/kaggle/working/VGG_01_FINAL.keras")

# Check if the predictions from the original and reconstructed models are similar
assert np.allclose(model_1.predict(test_img), reconstructed_model.predict(test_img)), "Outputs do not match!"
# Print a confirmation message if the outputs are the same
print("The original and reconstructed model outputs match.")

import tensorflow as tf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to load and preprocess an image
def load_and_prep_image(filename, img_shape=224):
    # Print the filename being loaded for debugging purposes
    print(f"Loading image: {filename}")
    # Read the image file
    img = tf.io.read_file(filename)
    # Decode the image into a tensor with 3 channels (RGB)
    img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3)
    # Resize the image to the target shape
    img = tf.image.resize(img, size=[img_shape, img_shape])
    # Normalize pixel values to be in the range [0, 1]
    img = img / 255.0
    return img

# Load and preprocess a specific test image from the directory
test_img_path = f"{test_dir}/Real/real_4.jpg"
test_img = load_and_prep_image(test_img_path)
# Add a batch dimension to the image tensor for model input
test_img_batch = tf.expand_dims(test_img, axis=0)

# Make a prediction with the loaded model
prediction = vgg_1.predict(test_img_batch)
# Print the prediction result
print(prediction)

# Display the processed image
plt.imshow(test_img)  # Show the image
plt.axis('off')  # Hide axes for a cleaner look
plt.show()  # Render the plot

Explanation:¶

  • Imports:

    • tensorflow as tf: Imports TensorFlow for model operations and image processing.
    • matplotlib.pyplot as plt: Imports Matplotlib for image visualization.

  • Function Definition (load_and_prep_image):

    • Input: Takes a filename (path to an image) and img_shape (desired image size, default is 224).
    • Image Loading:
      • Prints the name of the image file being loaded.
      • Reads the image file using tf.io.read_file.
    • Image Decoding:
      • Decodes the image into a tensor with 3 color channels (RGB).
    • Image Resizing:
      • Resizes the image to the specified dimensions (img_shape x img_shape).
    • Normalization:
      • Normalizes pixel values to be in the range [0, 1] by dividing by 255.
    • Return: Returns the preprocessed image tensor.

  • Load and Preprocess Test Image:

    • Defines the path to the test image (real_4.jpg) using test_dir.
    • Calls load_and_prep_image to load and preprocess the image, storing the result in test_img.
    • Adds a batch dimension to the image tensor for compatibility with the model's input using tf.expand_dims.

  • Make Prediction:

    • Uses the loaded model (vgg_1) to make a prediction on the preprocessed image batch (test_img_batch).
    • Prints the prediction result.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  # Import matplotlib for plotting

# Function to plot loss and accuracy curves separately
def plot_loss_curves(history):

    # Extract loss and accuracy data from training history
    loss = history.history['loss']  # Training loss values
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']  # Validation loss values

    accuracy = history.history['accuracy']  # Training accuracy values
    val_accuracy = history.history['val_accuracy']  # Validation accuracy values

    epochs = range(len(loss))  # Create a range for the number of epochs

    # Plot loss
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))  # Set figure size for loss plot
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, label='Training Loss')  # Plot training loss
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')  # Plot validation loss
    plt.title('Loss Curves')  # Set title for the loss plot
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')  # Label for the x-axis
    plt.ylabel('Loss')  # Label for the y-axis
    plt.legend()  # Display legend for the plot
    plt.grid(True)  # Add grid for better readability
    plt.show()  # Show the loss plot

    # Plot accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))  # Set figure size for accuracy plot
    plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, label='Training Accuracy')  # Plot training accuracy
    plt.plot(epochs, val_accuracy, label='Validation Accuracy')  # Plot validation accuracy
    plt.title('Accuracy Curves')  # Set title for the accuracy plot
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')  # Label for the x-axis
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')  # Label for the y-axis
    plt.legend()  # Display legend for the plot
    plt.grid(True)  # Add grid for better readability
    plt.show()  # Show the accuracy plot

# Usage example (assuming `history_1` is your training history):
plot_loss_curves(history_1)  # Call the function with training history

Explanation:¶

  • Imports: The code imports the pandas library for data manipulation and matplotlib.pyplot for plotting.

  • Data Preparation: The training history (stored in history_1) is converted into a DataFrame for easier handling and analysis.

  • Figure Creation: A figure is created for plotting, with a specified size of 10x7 inches.

  • Subplot for Accuracy:

    • The first subplot (2 rows, 1 column) is created to display training and validation accuracy over epochs.
    • Training accuracy is plotted in one line, and validation accuracy in another.
    • Titles, labels, and legends are added for clarity.

  • Subplot for Loss:

    • The second subplot displays training and validation loss over epochs.
    • Similar to the accuracy plot, training and validation losses are plotted with appropriate titles, labels, and legends.

  • Layout Adjustment: plt.tight_layout() is called to optimize the layout for better readability.

  • Display: Finally, the plots are displayed using plt.show().

In [12]:
# Import necessary libraries and modules
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam  # Optimizer for model training
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Flatten, Conv2D, MaxPool2D, Activation  # Layers for the model
from tensorflow.keras import Sequential  # Sequential model

tf.random.set_seed(42)  # Set random seed for reproducibility

# Define the model architecture
model_2 = Sequential([
    Conv2D(20, 3, activation='relu', input_shape=(224, 224, 3)),  # First convolutional layer with ReLU activation
    MaxPool2D(pool_size=2),  # Max pooling layer to reduce the feature map size by half
    Conv2D(20, 3, activation='relu'),  # Second convolutional layer with ReLU activation
    MaxPool2D(),  # Max pooling layer
    Conv2D(20, 3, activation='relu'),  # Third convolutional layer with ReLU activation
    MaxPool2D(),  # Max pooling layer
    Flatten(),  # Flatten the output to feed into the dense layer
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')  # Output layer for binary classification
])

# Compile the model with loss function, optimizer, and evaluation metrics
model_2.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',  # Binary cross-entropy loss for binary classification
                optimizer=Adam(),  # Adam optimizer
                metrics=['accuracy'])  # Track accuracy during training

# Fit the model on training data with validation
history_2 = model_2.fit(train_data,  # Training data
                        epochs=6,  # Number of training epochs
                        steps_per_epoch=256,  # Number of steps per epoch
                        validation_data=valid_data,  # Validation data
                        validation_steps=256)  # Number of validation steps

Explanation:¶

  1. Library Imports:

    • The code imports necessary components from TensorFlow's Keras API, which is used for building and training neural networks.

  2. Random Seed:

    • tf.random.set_seed(42): This sets a random seed for reproducibility, ensuring that the results can be replicated across different runs.

  3. Model Architecture:

    • A Sequential model (model_2) is defined using a stack of layers:
      • Conv2D Layers: These are convolutional layers that apply filters to the input images. Each layer uses ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit) activation to introduce non-linearity.
      • MaxPool2D Layers: These layers perform max pooling, reducing the spatial dimensions of the feature maps by half (or downsampling) to reduce computational load and prevent overfitting.
      • Flatten Layer: This layer flattens the output of the last convolutional layer into a one-dimensional array to prepare it for the dense layer.
      • Dense Layer: This is the output layer with a single neuron using the sigmoid activation function, suitable for binary classification tasks (outputting probabilities between 0 and 1).

  4. Model Compilation:

    • The model is compiled with:
      • Loss Function: binary_crossentropy, which is appropriate for binary classification problems.
      • Optimizer: The Adam optimizer, known for its efficiency and effectiveness in training deep learning models.
      • Metrics: The model will track accuracy during training.

  5. Model Training:

    • The model is trained using the fit method:
      • Training Data: Provided through train_data.
      • Number of Epochs: The model will train for 6 epochs.
      • Steps per Epoch: The number of batches to be processed in one epoch (256 in this case).
      • Validation Data: Used to evaluate the model's performance on unseen data after each epoch.
      • Validation Steps: Number of batches for validation (256).

import tensorflow as tf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def load_and_prep_image(filename, img_shape=224):
    # Read in the target file (an image)
    # print(f"Loading image: {filename}")  # Commented out to hide loading message
    img = tf.io.read_file(filename)  # Read the image file
    
    img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3)  # Decode the image into a 3-channel (RGB) format
    img = tf.image.resize(img, size=[img_shape, img_shape])  # Resize the image to the specified shape
    img = img / 255.0  # Normalize pixel values to the range [0, 1]
    
    return img

# Define your test directory (make sure this is set)
test_dir = "/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Test"

# Specify image paths for real and fake images
train_img_path_1 = f"{test_dir}/Real/real_10.jpg"  # Path to a real image
train_img_path_2 = f"{test_dir}/Fake/fake_100.jpg"  # Path to a fake image

# Load and preprocess the images
train_img_real_1 = load_and_prep_image(train_img_path_1)  # Load and prepare the real image
train_img_real_2 = load_and_prep_image(train_img_path_2)  # Load and prepare the fake image

# Expand dimensions to match model input shape (add batch dimension)
train_img_real_1 = tf.expand_dims(train_img_real_1, axis=0)
train_img_real_2 = tf.expand_dims(train_img_real_2, axis=0)

# Make predictions using the model
pred_1 = model_2.predict(train_img_real_1)  # Prediction for the real image
pred_2 = model_2.predict(train_img_real_2)  # Prediction for the fake image

# Print the predictions
print("Prediction for real image 1:", pred_1)
print("Prediction for fake image 2:", pred_2)

# Function to display images in a single row
def display_images_in_row(images, titles):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))  # Create a figure with specified size
    for i, image in enumerate(images):
        plt.subplot(1, len(images), i + 1)  # Create subplots in a single row
        plt.imshow(image)  # Display the image
        plt.title(titles[i])  # Set the title for the subplot
        plt.axis('off')  # Turn off axis numbers and ticks
    plt.show()  # Show the figure with the images

# Display the images in a single row
display_images_in_row(
    [tf.squeeze(train_img_real_1), tf.squeeze(train_img_real_2)],  # Remove batch dimension for display
    ["Real Image", "Fake Image"]  # Titles for the images
)

In [20]:
# Function to view a random image from a specified directory
def view_random_images(target_dirs, target_classes):
    num_images = len(target_classes)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_images, figsize=(15, 5))  # Adjust figsize as needed

    for i, (target_dir, target_class) in enumerate(zip(target_dirs, target_classes)):
        target_folder = os.path.join(target_dir, target_class)
        random_image = random.sample(os.listdir(target_folder), 1)
        img = mpimg.imread(os.path.join(target_folder, random_image[0]))
        axes[i].imshow(img)
        axes[i].set_title(target_class)
        axes[i].axis("off")
    
    plt.show()

# Display random images in a single row
view_random_images([train_dir, train_dir, valid_dir], ["Real", "Fake", "Real"])

6. Function to Extract Features Using ResNet50¶

  • directory: Path to the dataset directory.
  • num_samples: Number of samples to process per class.
  • classes: List of class labels.
  • For each class, load images, preprocess them, extract features using ResNet50, and store the features and labels.
In [23]:
def extract_features(directory, num_samples):
    features = []
    labels = []
    classes = ['Real', 'Fake']
    
    for class_label in classes:
        class_dir = directory + '/' + class_label
        for image_file in os.listdir(class_dir)[:num_samples]:
            image_path = class_dir + '/' + image_file
            image = load_img(image_path, target_size=(224, 224))
            image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)  # Ensure float32 type
            image = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
            image = datagen.standardize(image)
            features.append(model.predict(image)[0])
            labels.append(class_label)
    
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)

  • Load the ResNet50 model pre-trained on ImageNet without the top classification layer.
  • Use global average pooling to reduce the dimensions.

8. Extract Features from the Datasets¶

In [42]:
train_dir = '/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Train'
valid_dir = '/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Validation'
test_dir = '/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Test'

def extract_features(directory, num_samples):
    features = []
    labels = []
    classes = ['Real', 'Fake']
    
    for class_label in classes:
        class_dir = directory + '/' + class_label
        for image_file in os.listdir(class_dir)[:num_samples]:
            image_path = class_dir + '/' + image_file
            image = load_img(image_path, target_size=(224, 224))
            image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)
            image = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
            image = datagen.standardize(image)
            features.append(model.predict(image)[0])
            labels.append(class_label)
    
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)

model = ResNet50(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, pooling='avg')
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

num_samples_per_class = 100
X_train, y_train = extract_features(train_dir, num_samples_per_class)
X_valid, y_valid = extract_features(valid_dir, num_samples_per_class)
X_test, y_test = extract_features(test_dir, num_samples_per_class)

label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
y_train_encoded = label_encoder.fit_transform(y_train)
y_valid_encoded = label_encoder.transform(y_valid)
y_test_encoded = label_encoder.transform(y_test)

rf_classifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)
y_test_pred_rf = rf_classifier.predict(X_test)
accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_test_encoded, y_test_pred_rf)

logreg_classifier = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, max_iter=1000)
logreg_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)
y_test_pred_lr = logreg_classifier.predict(X_test)
accuracy_lr = accuracy_score(y_test_encoded, y_test_pred_lr)
In [45]:
# Generate confusion matrix for Random Forest
conf_mat = confusion_matrix(y_test_encoded, y_test_pred_rf)

# Plot confusion matrix with additional details
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.imshow(conf_mat, cmap=plt.cm.Greens)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - Random Forest")
plt.colorbar()
tick_marks = np.arange(len(label_encoder.classes_))
plt.xticks(tick_marks, label_encoder.classes_, rotation=45)
plt.yticks(tick_marks, label_encoder.classes_)
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
plt.ylabel('True Label')

# Add text annotations in the confusion matrix
thresh = conf_mat.max() / 2.
for i, j in np.ndindex(conf_mat.shape):
    plt.text(j, i, format(conf_mat[i, j], 'd'),
             ha="center", va="center",
             color="white" if conf_mat[i, j] > thresh else "black")

# Add overall accuracy and class information
num_samples = len(y_test)
class_counts = np.bincount(y_test_encoded)
accuracy_text = f"Overall Accuracy: {accuracy_rf:.2f}\n"
for i, class_label in enumerate(label_encoder.classes_):
    accuracy_text += f"{class_label}: {class_counts[i]} samples\n"

plt.gcf().text(0.95, 0.5, accuracy_text, fontsize=12, va='center', ha='right')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Import required libraries
import os
import random
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report, accuracy_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from tensorflow.keras.applications import ResNet50
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator, load_img

# Defining directory paths
train_dir = '/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Train'
valid_dir = '/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Validation'
test_dir = '/kaggle/input/deepfake-and-real-images/Dataset/Test'
In [47]:
# Function to view a random image from a specified directory
def view_random_images(target_dirs, target_classes):
    num_images = len(target_classes)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_images, figsize=(15, 5))  # Adjust figsize as needed

    for i, (target_dir, target_class) in enumerate(zip(target_dirs, target_classes)):
        target_folder = os.path.join(target_dir, target_class)
        random_image = random.sample(os.listdir(target_folder), 1)
        img = mpimg.imread(os.path.join(target_folder, random_image[0]))
        axes[i].imshow(img)
        axes[i].set_title(target_class)
        axes[i].axis("off")
    
    plt.show()

# Display random images in a single row
view_random_images([train_dir, train_dir, valid_dir], ["Real", "Fake", "Real"])
In [48]:
# Set up ImageDataGenerator for preprocessing
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

# Function to extract features using ResNet50
def extract_features(directory, num_samples):
    features = []
    labels = []
    classes = ['Real', 'Fake']
    
    for class_label in classes:
        class_dir = directory + '/' + class_label
        for image_file in os.listdir(class_dir)[:num_samples]:
            image_path = class_dir + '/' + image_file
            image = load_img(image_path, target_size=(224, 224))
            image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)  # Ensure float32 type
            image = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
            image = datagen.standardize(image)
            features.append(model.predict(image)[0])
            labels.append(class_label)
    
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)

# Load ResNet50 model for feature extraction
model = ResNet50(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, pooling='avg')

# Plot confusion matrix for Logistic Regression
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.imshow(conf_mat_lr, cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - Logistic Regression")
plt.colorbar()
tick_marks = np.arange(len(label_encoder.classes_))
plt.xticks(tick_marks, label_encoder.classes_, rotation=45)
plt.yticks(tick_marks, label_encoder.classes_)
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
plt.ylabel('True Label')

# Add text annotations
thresh = conf_mat_lr.max() / 2.
for i, j in np.ndindex(conf_mat_lr.shape):
    plt.text(j, i, format(conf_mat_lr[i, j], 'd'),
             ha="center", va="center",
             color="Black" if conf_mat_lr[i, j] > thresh else "white")

plt.show()

In [71]:
# Directories for training, validation, and test datasets
def extract_features(directory, num_samples):
    features = []  # To store extracted features
    labels = []  # To store corresponding labels
    classes = ['Real', 'Fake']  # Class labels

    # Iterate over each class
    for class_label in classes:
        class_dir = directory + '/' + class_label  # Directory for the current class
        # Iterate over each image file in the class directory (up to num_samples)
        for image_file in os.listdir(class_dir)[:num_samples]:
            image_path = class_dir + '/' + image_file  # Path to the current image
            image = load_img(image_path, target_size=(224, 224))  # Load and resize the image
            image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)  # Convert image to numpy array with float32 type
            image = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)  # Expand dimensions to fit the model input
            image = datagen.standardize(image)  # Standardize the image
            features.append(model.predict(image)[0])  # Extract features using the model and append
            labels.append(class_label)  # Append the class label
    
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)  # Return features and labels as numpy arrays
In [72]:
# Load the ResNet50 model pre-trained on ImageNet, excluding the top layer, and use average pooling
model = ResNet50(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, pooling='avg')

# Create an ImageDataGenerator for rescaling images
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

# Number of samples to extract per class
num_samples_per_class = 50  # Adjust based on your dataset

# Extract features and labels from the training dataset
X_train, y_train = extract_features(train_dir, num_samples_per_class)
# Extract features and labels from the validation dataset
X_valid, y_valid = extract_features(valid_dir, num_samples_per_class)
# Extract features and labels from the test dataset
X_test, y_test = extract_features(test_dir, num_samples_per_class)

# Initialize a LabelEncoder to encode the class labels
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
# Fit the encoder on the training labels and transform them
y_train_encoded = label_encoder.fit_transform(y_train)
# Transform the validation labels
y_valid_encoded = label_encoder.transform(y_valid)
# Transform the test labels
y_test_encoded = label_encoder.transform(y_test)

Train Random Forest Classifier¶

In [73]:
# Initialize a RandomForestClassifier with 100 trees and a fixed random state for reproducibility
rf_classifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)

# Train the Random Forest classifier using the extracted features and encoded training labels
rf_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Predict the class labels for the validation set using the trained classifier
y_valid_pred_rf = rf_classifier.predict(X_valid)

# Calculate the accuracy of the predictions on the validation set
accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_valid_encoded, y_valid_pred_rf)

# Print the validation accuracy of the Random Forest classifier
print(f"Random Forest Validation Accuracy: {accuracy_rf:.4f}")

Random Forest Validation Accuracy: 0.5700

Train Logistic Regression Classifier¶

In [74]:
# Initialize a LogisticRegression classifier with a fixed random state for reproducibility and a maximum of 1000 iterations
logreg_classifier = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, max_iter=1000)

# Train the Logistic Regression classifier using the extracted features and encoded training labels
logreg_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Predict the class labels for the validation set using the trained classifier
y_valid_pred_lr = logreg_classifier.predict(X_valid)

# Calculate the accuracy of the predictions on the validation set
accuracy_lr = accuracy_score(y_valid_encoded, y_valid_pred_lr)

# Print the validation accuracy of the Logistic Regression classifier
print(f"Logistic Regression Validation Accuracy: {accuracy_lr:.4f}")

Logistic Regression Validation Accuracy: 0.5100

# Combine training and validation sets for PCA
X_combined = np.concatenate((X_train, X_valid), axis=0)
y_combined = np.concatenate((y_train_encoded, y_valid_encoded), axis=0)

# Perform PCA to reduce to 2 dimensions
pca = PCA(n_components=2, random_state=42)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_combined)
In [77]:
# Create a scatter plot for Random Forest predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))  # Set the figure size

# Scatter plot for Random Forest predictions with PCA components and using viridis colormap
scatter_rf = plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=y_combined, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.6, label='Random Forest Predictions')

# Scatter plot for Logistic Regression predictions with PCA components and using plasma colormap
plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=y_combined, cmap='plasma', alpha=0.4, label='Logistic Regression Predictions')

# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('PCA Scatter Plot of Random Forest and Logistic Regression Predictions')
# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')

# Get handles and labels for the legend from the scatter plot for Random Forest predictions
handles, labels = scatter_rf.legend_elements(prop='colors')
# Add the legend to the plot, using the classes from the label encoder
plt.legend(handles, label_encoder.classes_, title='Classes')

# Display the plot
plt.show()
In [97]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator, load_img
from tensorflow.keras.applications import ResNet50
import os

# Function to extract features
def extract_features(directory, num_samples):
    features = []
    labels = []
    classes = ['Real', 'Fake']
    
    for class_label in classes:
        class_dir = directory + '/' + class_label
        for image_file in os.listdir(class_dir)[:num_samples]:
            image_path = class_dir + '/' + image_file
            image = load_img(image_path, target_size=(224, 224))
            image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)
            image = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
            image = datagen.standardize(image)
            features.append(model.predict(image)[0])
            labels.append(class_label)
    
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)

# Initialize model and data generator
model = ResNet50(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, pooling='avg')
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

# Extract features from the datasets
num_samples_per_class = 100
X_train, y_train = extract_features(train_dir, num_samples_per_class)
X_valid, y_valid = extract_features(valid_dir, num_samples_per_class)
X_test, y_test = extract_features(test_dir, num_samples_per_class)

# Encode labels
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
y_train_encoded = label_encoder.fit_transform(y_train)
y_valid_encoded = label_encoder.transform(y_valid)
y_test_encoded = label_encoder.transform(y_test)

# Train Random Forest Classifier
rf_classifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)
y_test_pred_rf = rf_classifier.predict(X_test)
accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_test_encoded, y_test_pred_rf)

# Train Logistic Regression Classifier
logreg_classifier = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, max_iter=1000)
logreg_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)
y_test_pred_lr = logreg_classifier.predict(X_test)
accuracy_lr = accuracy_score(y_test_encoded, y_test_pred_lr)

# Perform PCA to reduce dimensionality to 2D for visualization
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_test)

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Scatter plot for Random Forest predictions
scatter_rf = plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=y_test_pred_rf, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.6, label='Random Forest Predictions')

# Scatter plot for Logistic Regression predictions
scatter_lr = plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=y_test_pred_lr, cmap='plasma', alpha=0.4, label='Logistic Regression Predictions')

# Set plot title and labels
plt.title('PCA Scatter Plot of Random Forest and Logistic Regression Predictions')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')

# Add legend for Random Forest
handles_rf, _ = scatter_rf.legend_elements(prop='colors')
legend_rf = plt.legend(handles_rf, label_encoder.classes_, loc="upper right", title="Random Forest Classes")
plt.gca().add_artist(legend_rf)

# Add legend for Logistic Regression
handles_lr, _ = scatter_lr.legend_elements(prop='colors')
plt.legend(handles_lr, label_encoder.classes_, loc="lower right", title="Logistic Regression Classes")

# Display the plot
plt.show()
